## Rules for test files [glob: **/test_*.py]
- Every test function must have a docstring explaining what it's testing
- Use pytest fixtures, not setUp/tearDown
- Mock all external API calls — tests should never make real network requests
- Tests must be in the same folder as the file they are testing
- Tests must be named test_*.py
- Tests must take place before the actual code is written
- Tests must be runnable with pytest
- Tests must be independent of each other
- Tests must be written in the same language as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same style as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same format as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same structure as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same syntax as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same conventions as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same best practices as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same documentation as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same comments as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same logging as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same error handling as the code they are testing
- Tests must be written in the same debugging as the code they are testing

## Rules for route handlers [glob: app.py]
- Every route must validate its inputs before processing
- Routes return JSON for /api/* paths, HTML for everything else
- Never put business logic directly in a route — call a function from fetcher.py instead
- Routes must be named route_*.py
- Routes must be in the same folder as the file they are testing
- Routes must be named route_*.py
- Routes must take place before the actual code is written
- Routes must be runnable with pytest
- Routes must be independent of each other

## Hard rules:
- API keys in `.env` only. Hardcoded key = exercise doesn't count.
- `fetcher.py` is separate from `app.py`. Routes do not contain API logic.
- Use the AI terminal (Cmd+K) for all shell operations today.
- Use `@docs` when asking about Flask or APScheduler APIs.
- Update your architecture Notepad whenever you make a structural decision.
- App must run cleanly with `flask run` before you commit.